  <div class="article-body">

<p>McKinsey's <em>Workforce 2030</em> report, published in May 2026, contains one number: by 2030, 30% of work tasks will be completed through tripartite collaboration between humans, agents, and robots.</p>

<p>I spent an afternoon reading that report, and another evening reading the two other McKinsey reports published in the same period (on clean technology and agricultural commodity trading). All three point to the same underlying signal: <strong>tripartite collaboration is not a concept — it is becoming a quantifiable trend.</strong></p>

<p>Then I closed the reports and opened my phone. Yicai Global had just pushed a story:</p>

<blockquote>"Chinese embodied AI companies enter manufacturing and convenience stores — commercial deployment validation completed."</blockquote>

<p>That's not a coincidence.</p>

<h2>Three Roles of Tripartite Collaboration</h2>

<p>Across the three McKinsey reports, AI plays three distinct roles.</p>

<p><strong>In the labor report,</strong> AI is the "amplifier." Not replacing humans, but expanding human capability — one worker plus one AI agent can do the work of three. The report estimates productivity gains of 15% to 30% for such combinations, depending on the industry's digital maturity.</p>

<p><strong>In the clean technology report,</strong> AI is the "transformer." Energy system optimization, carbon capture efficiency improvement, new materials discovery cycles — AI's role in these areas is not to "do it better" but to "do what was previously impossible."</p>

<p><strong>In the agricultural commodity trading report,</strong> AI is the "compressor." The chain from field data to futures pricing is being compressed by AI — market changes that once took three months to analyze can now go from data to decision in three days.</p>

<p>Three roles, one underlying logic: <strong>humans make judgments and choices, agents analyze and coordinate, robots execute and repeat.</strong></p>

<p>This is not a theoretical framework. It is what is happening today.</p>

<h2>Tripartite Collaboration in a Convenience Store</h2>

<p>Yicai Global's report describes a specific scenario.</p>

<p>A Chinese embodied AI company's product has entered convenience stores — not as a demo, not as a POC, but as a real commercial operation. The product covers two use cases:</p>

<p><strong>First, assisted checkout judgments.</strong> When a customer's purchases trigger a recognition dispute (e.g., buying two packs of the same cigarettes but only one is scanned), AI doesn't make the final call. It analyzes on-site camera data and presents the "most likely option" — the store clerk makes the final confirmation. Humans at the judgment layer, AI at the information layer.</p>

<p><strong>Second, shelf anomaly detection.</strong> Smart devices automatically inspect shelves during off-hours. When stock is low, they don't directly order replenishment — they push a "low-stock items + suggested restock quantities" report to the store manager, who decides based on actual conditions (recent sales velocity, upcoming promotions, etc.). Machines execute, agents suggest, humans decide.</p>

<p>No sci-fi. No flashy demos. Almost mundane.</p>

<p>But this is what tripartite collaboration looks like in practice — not robots replacing store clerks, but making the clerk's judgment more valuable.</p>

<h2>Four Common Bottlenecks</h2>

<p>McKinsey's reports repeatedly identify four bottlenecks that hinder tripartite collaboration deployment.</p>

<p><strong>Data quality.</strong> The ceiling of any collaboration depends on the quality of input data. In the convenience store scenario, checkout dispute recognition accuracy ranges from 97% to 99% — that missing 1% to 3% is not because AI is not good enough, but because the training data annotation quality is insufficient. This is not a technology problem. It is an engineering problem.</p>

<p><strong>Organizational agility.</strong> Organizations implementing tripartite collaboration need the ability to adjust "what humans do, what agents do, what machines do" at any time. McKinsey's research found that successfully deploying organizations share one characteristic: <strong>the boundary between human and AI responsibilities is reassessed every quarter</strong> — not "set once, frozen for three years."</p>

<p><strong>Trust governance.</strong> In the agricultural commodity trading scenario, a senior executive at a Chinese private futures firm asked me: "When AI gives me a buy signal and I trust it and lose money — who is responsible?" There is no technical answer to this question. It requires an organizational trust governance framework — who is accountable for AI outputs in which scenarios, and who has the authority to override AI decisions.</p>

<p><strong>Talent transformation.</strong> Not "humans will be replaced" but "humans will become something else." The convenience store clerk's role shifts from "managing shelves" to "making judgments informed by AI recommendations." This transformation is not free — it means redefining job descriptions, redesigning compensation, and retraining every frontline employee.</p>

<p>The four bottlenecks and three roles match perfectly — each role hits at least one bottleneck when deployed.</p>

<h2>One Last Question</h2>

<p>If you ask "when will tripartite collaboration arrive," the answer is: it's already here.</p>

<p>If you ask "but what about my industry" — McKinsey used three unrelated industries (labor, clean tech, agriculture) to prove one point: <strong>this is not an industry problem. It is a paradigm problem.</strong></p>

<p>Which of the three roles does your industry most closely resemble? Are you the one being amplified, the one being transformed, or the one being compressed?</p>

<p>That's not an easy question to answer.</p>

<p>But it is the most important strategic question you will face next quarter.</p>

